		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Name of the Wind gets TV Show
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1788935">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>PPatty</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1788928#post1788928" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Don't know anything about these books. How good are they, and what other fantasy series might serve as comparisons?</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Its a tough one to compare it to. In some ways its a little like the Farseer Trilogy (I think thats the one with Virtue, and FitzChivalry, right?) and then in a couple of other ways it a little bit like the Magician combo/Riftwar with nothing to do with the riftwar at all, but thats only focusing on a smaller aspect of it. <br />
<br />
There's a significant portion of the first book that is almost lifted off the pages from book 1 of The Wizard of Earthsea. <br />
<br />
You can tell by reading it, that the author put more of himself into the main character than anything, and made everything an allegory for his experiences of life, including the way the narrator, the protagonist, and the author (which is cleverly seperated into 3 different people, and 3 frames of reference) are all separate rationalizations for the things he did in his life. <br />
<br />
I know a lot of people who don't read fantasy that like it just for that, and then of course, the normal fantasy heads who enjoy it at face value. The first book is a swift read, and the second book is even quicker. I'd say there's about 2,000 pages between them, and they were over and done with for me in less than a week.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
		<div class="postfoot">
